---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "ECS cost model beyond compute: the checklist that prevents surprise bills";
const description =
  "A practical ECS cost model checklist beyond compute: load balancers, logs/metrics, NAT/egress, cross-AZ transfer, and storage. Use it to avoid underestimating ECS total cost.";
const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why is compute-only a bad ECS estimate?",
    a: "Because ECS bills often include large non-compute line items: ALB/NLB baseline and capacity units, log ingestion and retention, NAT gateway processed traffic, and internet egress.",
  },
  {
    q: "What line item is most commonly underestimated?",
    a: "Logs and networking. Verbose services can generate large ingestion + retention costs, and container fleets can generate substantial NAT processed traffic (image pulls, updates, external APIs).",
  },
  {
    q: "Whatâ€™s the fastest way to build an ECS TCO model?",
    a: "Start with compute (tasks or instances), then add load balancers, logs, and data transfer. Use calculators to estimate each line item and sum.",
  },
];
---
<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/aws-ecs-cost-model-beyond-compute"
  lastUpdated="2026-01-22"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>
    ECS cost surprises usually happen when teams budget only for compute (EC2 instance-hours or Fargate vCPU/GB-hours).
    In real services, the big costs often come from <strong>load balancers</strong>, <strong>logs</strong>, and{" "}
    <strong>networking</strong>. Use this checklist to build a more accurate model.
  </p>

  <h2>1) Compute (baseline)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ECS on Fargate</strong>: vCPU-hours + memory GB-hours.</li>
    <li><strong>ECS on EC2</strong>: instance-hours (plus EBS if used).</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-fargate-cost-calculator/">Fargate cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/ec2-cost-calculator/">EC2 cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-ecs-ec2-vs-fargate-cost-calculator/">ECS EC2 vs Fargate (compare)</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-ecs-task-sizing-calculator/">ECS task sizing</a>
  </div>

  <h2>2) Load balancers (baseline + capacity)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>ALB/NLB hourly baseline per load balancer.</li>
    <li>Capacity units (LCU/NLCU) driven by connections, new connections, throughput, and rule evaluations.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-load-balancer-cost-calculator/">Load balancer cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-load-balancer-cost/">Load balancer cost guide</a>
  </div>

  <h2>3) Logs and metrics (often bigger than compute)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Log ingestion is proportional to request volume and verbosity.</li>
    <li>Retention creates a steady GB-month storage baseline.</li>
    <li>Query scan costs can add an extra variable component.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/log-cost-calculator/">Log cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/log-costs/">Log cost guide</a>
  </div>

  <h2>4) Networking (NAT, egress, cross-AZ)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>NAT gateway</strong>: hourly + GB processed can spike for fleets pulling images/updates behind NAT.</li>
    <li><strong>Internet egress</strong>: downloads, APIs, and public traffic.</li>
    <li><strong>Cross-AZ transfer</strong>: chatty microservices, load balancer routing patterns, and multi-AZ replication.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-nat-gateway-cost/">NAT gateway cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-cross-az-data-transfer-cost/">Cross-AZ transfer cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Data egress cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/vpc-data-transfer-cost-calculator/">VPC transfer cost</a>
  </div>

  <h2>5) Storage (if you run on EC2 or attach volumes)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>EBS volumes and snapshots (plus IOPS/throughput for some volume types).</li>
    <li>Database storage growth and backups for stateful services.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-ebs-cost-calculator/">EBS cost</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-ebs-pricing/">EBS pricing guide</a>
  </div>

  <h2>6) Put it together (sum line items)</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Pick the compute model (Fargate vs EC2) and estimate average monthly capacity.</li>
    <li>Add load balancer baseline and estimate capacity units.</li>
    <li>Add logs (ingestion + retention) and validate verbosity assumptions.</li>
    <li>Add networking (NAT/egress/cross-AZ) for the real traffic paths.</li>
    <li>Add storage where applicable (EBS and snapshots).</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="muted" style="margin-top:14px">
    Related: <a href="/guides/aws-ecs-pricing/">ECS pricing</a>,{" "}
    <a href="/guides/aws-ecs-autoscaling-cost-pitfalls/">ECS autoscaling cost pitfalls</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Validation checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Validate the primary driver with measured usage from a representative window.</li>
    <li>Confirm units and pricing units (per 10k vs per 1M, GB vs GiB) before trusting the estimate.</li>
    <li>Re-check incident windows: retries/timeouts often multiply cost drivers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related reading</h2>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/cloud-cost-estimation-checklist/">Cost estimation checklist</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/network-transfer-costs/">Network transfer costs</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/request-based-pricing/">Request-based pricing</a>
  </div>

</GuideLayout>
